Harvard students take classes at sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University has provided all students with more sleep in an attempt to resist the growing tendency of students to stay awake and learn all night with the help of caffeine tablets.
A study found that students at the world's best universities often know little or nothing when it comes to the basics of thinking about themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and the Women's Hospital, designed the course and believes it sees the first of its kind in the United States.
He came up with the idea of doing the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning ability.
‘At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I told this first now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he said toTelegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help student skills and performance in sports and even contribute to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the school's health care, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were extremely sleepless during the week.
The course is hourly in length and includes various interactive tasks.
One section depicts a room in a dormitory, where students click on cup of coffee, curtains, sports shoes, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how performance in sports can worsen with lack of sleep, along with the importance of good routine before sleep.
In another section, participants are told how a long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the school area with interactive symbols then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“ We know that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we feel they have a right to know this, just as one is entitled to know of the health effects of smoking cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture that favors those who stay awake and learn all night is still there, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-growing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
The guarantee of gaining sufficient sleep of good quality should be a "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight loss, because sleep deprivation increases the brain's call for food so that the body is constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old in chemical and physical biology from California, helped Professor Czeisler put the course together, but he sat one of the professor's curates last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to call for a course for all students at school.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all faculty members to complete a similar course before starting their studies at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider tuning an alarm clock, which reminds them to go to sleep, and to wake them, noting the harmful effects from blue light produced by electronic screens and LED lights, which can confuse the body's inner clock and lead to trouble falling into sleep.
