The latest news of algae blooms: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest reports from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission show a general decrease in concentrations of algae flowers in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, worn-out algae flowers are reported in certain areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota Charlotte and Collier counties - indicating decreasing concentrations.
The algae flower covers approximately 200 miles of shoreline from northern Pinellas to southern Lee County.
Individual flowers can be found about 10 miles (16 km) from Hillsborough County, but at fewer locations compared to last week.
There have also been reports of algae flowers in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations at or near Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off the coasts of Hillsborough County, extremely low to high concentrations in Manatee County, extremely low to high concentrations in or on the shores of Sarasota County, extremely low to moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, extremely low to high concentrations in or on the shores of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported in northwestern Florida over the previous week.
